Programs often have a purpose for the user. In this course, we've been focused on 
theoretical structures to theoretical programs, so we have't had to worry about what 
the output of our programs would be used for, but for a real, industry developed 
program, the user would want to be able to have some sort of save feature so that 
their experience could be kept track of, whether for recordkeeping or understanding.
 For example, a player playing a game probably doesn't need a reciept because the 
 experience is meant to be expereinced, rather than used for some sort of important 
 function that needs to be kept track of, like a writing program or a workplace 
 communication app, where the user would want a record of the input given to the 
 program.

Storing/saving that information allows the user to share it with others, and if the program is changing or compiling information given to it, the user would want a copy of the output. Think of how you'd get a reciept for buying something at the store, but you wouldn't make a list or get a receipt of items you were just glancing at.